                    <span>The author is interesting and unique in that he himself admitted to once being a typical "backlash" conservative until he found himself facing reality and then did what most in Kansas would call unthinkable and that is vote Democratic though he voted for Nader in 2000 and Kerry in 2004. I got to say, I've been feeling the same way ever since Nov 2, 2004 when it was the last day I've proudly shot myself in the foot by voting for the same old Republican party that does nothing to live up to its promises on what they claim to do about hot button issues while at the same time doing their utmost best and succeeding at keeping the economy out of the discussion or at least giving false positive spin like what the Labor Dept did which was to invent some false numbers to show that jobs are being created even when it's not so and it's likely that most of those jobs are being created in other countries. Yes, in every presidential election I happily voted for the Republican candidate after being fed up with the Democratic Party for not showing up in our state and giving us voters something to think about and instead inventing silly fears and excuses that we voters will think they're too liberal and that it will result in more conservative turnout even when it should be obvious that it hasn't and will not ever work that way. Even Tom Daschle who supposed to be a strong leader for the Democratic Party as an opposition to the bullying Republican Party couldn't discipline Senate Democrats in all his years as Senate Leader got kicked out by a newcomer, well sort of newcomer as he's been in the House of Representatives before challenging the other senator Tim Johnson who narrowly won in 2002. Surely if Tom Daschle hadn't pandered I would have voted for him and if John Kerry had showed up and been more firm about his take on the issues I and likely more voters in my state of South Dakota and some other red states would have given Kerry the keys to the White House instead of detaining him as just another U.S. Senator out of 100.
<br />
<br />Well, I read this book and now I'm beginning to think "You know what? The Republicans never keep their promises on the social issues once elections are over and they talk little about the economy during the election or present false data and then after the election do the unthinkable on the economy by carrying out orders from special interests and lobbyists in crafting economic legislation that only hurts us average Joes who went through all the trouble to support the Republicans based on false promises of what they plan to do on hot-button issues." Until the Republicans can get their act together and do the right stuff, they can forget my vote from now on. Maybe that's what "W. R. Salber" is so afraid of besides the fact that virtually all of the books he desperately recommends are beginning to lose ground and just don't click. Now that doesn't mean I'll automatically vote Democrat because they too need to clean up their act by putting the economic issues back on the table and truly standing up for the people they claim to stand up for as Thomas Frank implies as a suggested solution to this mess in this book. Look, I don't care about one's position on gay marriage vs traditional marriage or for that matter gun rights vs gun control or abortion vs no choice or pro-god vs atheist. I don't want to hear about it. And yes, it is extremely embarrasing that my state has to be one of the few which allows pharmacists to refuse birth controls pills if they simply feel like it and are usually anti-abortion. My concern is economic safety and Thomas Frank gets my vote for the best book when it comes to understanding the true nature of disaffected and apathetic voters and even blind supporters of conservatives which I used to be. 
<br />
<br />P.S.: If you want to know the real dangers of a national sales tax that conservatives and libertarians are working to push, then come to my state of South Dakota which is one of the few states to have a state sales tax with no state income tax and you'll see.</span>
                  
