                    <span>I am an educated and hard-working man; active in my church and community; a husband, father, home owner and... a Republican.  I often recommend books to my misguided Liberal friends and relatives to help them see the error of their ways.  I thought I should, out of fairness, take a look at something from the Liberal camp just for the intellectual exercise.  
<br />There is nothing here but a lot of whining and screeching from a confused and frightened individual.  Frank begins and ends on the assumption that the Democratic party is the benevolent caretaker of all humanmankind and that one would have to be ignorant and deranged not to support them.  
<br />Humankind deserves better than socialism and that is what the Democrats are peddling.  
<br />I can't believe a Lefty allowed trees to be killed for this drivel. 
<br /></span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">What's the Matter with (YOUR STATE'S NAME HERE)...?</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>6</span>
                      /
                      <span>7</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-15</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>This carefully edited, lucid analysis of the social, philosophical, economic and psychological mechanisms the Right have used so skillfully to convince citizens (who were most abused by the Right) to champion its causes, is only vindicated again. 
<br />
<br />Today, May 15, national news reports state that the Kansas State School Board is proposing to redefine "Science."  Had we a Galileo, Kepler, Freud, Darwin or Feynmann or Crick down there, I might take some interest in the story. As it is, the Kansas story bespeaks the same totalitarian, absolutist mush that has made today's America as grim as it is, and its position in the world community as tenuous.  Let's not even discuss economics.   Don't even e-mail the word; someone may be tapping your computer.
<br />
<br />The one piece Tom Frank might have added to his argument is that class warfare in America has become so brazen and offensive that some of  the working poor may support Republicans because they hope for upward mobility themselves.  A ridiculous concept, I know, but we haave all become a bit ridiculous in the eyes of half the country and much of the world.
<br />
<br />As for the ideological use Republicans have made of Jesus of Nazareth, I'll leave that one for historians and theologians; for while many Republicans have postured and railed against "Liberals" (a term for which few, if any, have provided a concise definition) they have changed little in America's ethical or moral agenda -- except to make it more ambiguous.
<br />
<br />In large part, today's Republicans (who do not technically represent the party of Lincoln) have one primary objective -- as Frank describes so well:
<br />absolute economic primacy based on the continued suppression of those who are less privileged -- and by using a variety of pseudo-spiritual, pseudo-theological and odd socioeconomic methods to maake it happen.
<br />
<br />The "Democrats," having abdicated their mission for years, have lost credibility even among Democrats.  The New Deal is history.  Ducks flying into the sunset.
<br />
<br />And so what Frank exposes in this thoughtful book is the yawning void that threatens to overtake -- by eradicating all true moral and ethical principles -- our trading floors, legislatures, courts, schools, offices, prisons, doctor's offices, psychologist's offices -- everything in fact.
<br />
<br />I no longer consider myself a Democrat. I wouldn't dare My party has failed too often and has succumbed to the same self-serving dance as the Republican party.  Go for Fascism or aa Democratic Republic and then work for it -- one or the other.
<br />
<br />Behind all this unmitigated political junk -- put in motion by (mostly) privileged white men and women in suits --  are the realities of a society on the ecological, moral, economic and behavioral brink -- of failing all progressive history, of all progress. Moral, spiritual, even technological in the long run.
<br />
<br />No global warming, indeed.
<br />
<br />Thomas Frank has written a book that is, in the best sense, a mirror for Republicans and "Democrats."  It should open the eyes of both, and if it does not, someone isn't reading carefully enough.
<br />
<br />Time to wake up and remember that tea party.</span>
                  
              
